Integration test that lints the real `dict.steno` corpus for stroke key ordering, not the steno crate's own logic — it exercises `parse_source`, `parse_stroke`, and `render_stroke` from the `steno` crate against production data rather than synthetic fixtures.

The critical fact: `parse_stroke` is lenient (accepts keys in any order within a bank) and `render_stroke` silently normalizes to canonical order (`#STKPWHRAO*EUFRPBLGTS`, per `LEFT_ORDER`/`MID_ORDER`/`RIGHT_ORDER`), so a mis-ordered stroke in `dict.steno` parses and renders fine elsewhere in the build — nothing else catches it. This test is that check: it parses the whole dictionary, then for every sub-stroke of every entry, round-trips it through `parse_stroke` + `render_stroke` and asserts the output equals the original literal text. Any mismatch means the source stroke wasn't already in canonical bank order.

`DICT` is loaded via `include_str!` pointing two directories up from `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR` to the repo-root `dict.steno` — if that file moves relative to `crates/steno/`, this path breaks. Failure output batches every violation found (not just the first) into one panic message, each line citing the source line number, the offending sub-stroke, the full raw stroke string it came from, and the expected canonical form, to make bulk-fixing the dictionary easier. Also asserts the parsed entry list is non-empty, guarding against the include path silently resolving to an empty or missing file.